        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity - The ALMA field of view at the expected frequency of CO(1-0) for a target at z= 0.0446 is of ~ 56´´. 
The whole galaxy group has an extent of 35´´, therefore it fits entirely into a single pointing in Band 3, centered at R.A.=17:20:28.132, Dec=-67:46:28.753. 
To estimate the expected distribution of CO and its flux density for individual group components, we used the Halpha emission-line map 
from our integral-field observations as a reasonable model for the 
expected molecular gas emission. The map covers the whole group 
except for its optically fainter tidal tail on the western side 
(Fig. 1). We converted the Halpha fluxes to expected CO fluxes in 
units of Jy km/s by using as a conversion factor the ratio between 
the estimated total CO flux (§1.1) and the measured total Halpha 
flux, F(Halpha) = 9.5 x 10^(-14) erg/s/cm^2. 
This conversion assumes a homogeneous star formation efficiency
across the group, which appears reasonable for its star-forming 
components. 
The expected line-width based on Halpha emission-line kinematics of 
the individual galaxies, HII region complexes, and tidal dwarf 
galaxy candidates ranges between 30 and 400 km/s. 
These velocities, combined with the above Halpha-to-CO flux 
conversion imply expected fluxes of ~ 32 mJy, 5.2 mJy, and 17.6 mJy 
for the two spiral galaxies and the brightest tidal dwarf candidate. The diameters of these objects range from 6´´ to 10´´. For the 
faintest star-forming clumps (on a 3´´ scale) that we plan to sample along the tidal tail, we estimate a flux density of about 4.0 
mJy/beam. Therefore we request a sensitivity of 0.8 mJy with an 
angular resolution of 1.0´´ as a good compromise for resolving 
sufficient structures across the galaxy group and detect the 
faintest clumps with S/N ~ 5. On the brightest group components we 
expect to reach a S/N &lt;~ 30.
A velocity resolution of 6km/s will be sufficient to detect 
rotational motions in the tidal dwarf galaxy candidates, that, based on observations of Halpha line emission have velocity gradients of 
order of 20 km/s. For the weakest emission components we can analyze the data with a coarser velocity resolution to increase the S/N 
ratio to obtain a secure detection and a measure of the total flux.

With these choices the total time for the science goal is of 12.69h, as estimated by the OT including calibration and overheads and using the compact array with the TP antennas. 
However, we estimate that the ACA-7m array would be sufficient to 
recover the emission on our largest angular scale of interest 
(35´´, i.e. the extent of the galaxies together with the tidal tails departing from them). Without the TP antennas, the total time for 
the science goal would be of 8.07h split in 3.46h (of which 1.18h on source) with 2 configurations of the 12m array and 4.61h with the 
ACA-7m array.

Imaging - We ask for a single pointing in extended configuration 
with 1´´ angular resolution, combined with ACA, at the sky frequency of the 12CO (J=1-0) transition, 110.35 GHz. 
The chosen velocity channel binning to a resolution of 
6 km/s will allow us to reach a S/N ~ 5 on the faintest clumps (0.8 
mJy/beam).
CASA simulations show that the requested exposure time will give us 
the appropriate u-v coverage to reconstruct and identify the 
expected substructures across the system (Fig. 1).

Correlator setup - We use a 1.8 GHz bandwidth and a Hanning smoothed frequency resolution of 976 kHz averaged on 4 velocity channels to a final resolution of 1.938 MHz (~ 5.3 km/s). Our optical observations indicate velocity widths &lt; 400km/s, so even our largest velocities 
are well sampled within the ~ 1280 km/s bandwidth around the CO line with enough bandwidth left for the adjacent continuum.
One of the basebands is centered at the sky frequency of the CO(1-0) line, and the other three basebands are centered at contiguous 
frequencies, in order to measure the continuum emission in the whole bandwidth. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
