    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>In hierarchical models, compact galaxy groups that evolve in isolation are
possible precursors to field elliptical galaxies. CG J1720-67.8 is one of
the most compact groups known to date, it displays the hallmarks of strong
mutual interactions and possible tidal dwarf galaxy formation.
The system is probably caught during the rapid, hence rare to observe,
process of final coalescence. This is maybe the reason why it stands out
also for its wide-spread, strongly enhanced star formation activity at
levels that are rarely seen in local universe compact groups.
We propose to map the distribution of molecular gas and dust across this
exceptional and complex system by observing the 12CO (J=1-0) transition
and the adjacent continuum in one single pointing. These new observations,
combined with the wealth of multiwavelength data already obtained by our
team, will give us the opportunity to investigate how the final
coalescence process can affect the star formation efficiency of small
galaxy groups.</prp:abstract>
